<F P=100> CENTRAL AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Congo </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government, Opposition Clash 31 Dec; 4 Dead in Bacongo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0201145394 Paris AFP in English 1442 GMT 2 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0201145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brazzaville, Jan 2 (AFP) -- At least four people 
died and many others were shot when government forces and 
opposition militiamen clashed in Brazzaville's southern Bacongo 
district, hospital officials announced Sunday [2 January]. 
Military officials said the clashes overnight Friday broke out 
after armed opposition rebels, identified as "ninjas," attacked 
an army camp at Bacongo. The army used heavy weapons to repel 
the submachine-gun toting rebels. 
  But opposition spokesman Laurent Mann accused the members of 
the national police's ministerial reserve of attacking the 
opposition militia and "shooting at passers-by at close range." 
Mann said the number of casualties was much higher and five 
bodies had still not been retrieved from Bacongo as no Red Cross 
workers had been allowed in. 
  The worst violence ended Saturday afternoon but witnesses 
said shots could still be heard at Bacongo Sunday morning. 
  At least 93 people have died since new violence erupted in 
the southern neighborhoods of the Congolese capital between 
supporters of the government and the opposition in early 
December, according to a hospital tally. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

