<F P=100> EAST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Somalia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Thousands' Sign Petition on Foreign Troops To Leave </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  EA3012203593 (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People in Somali 1700 GMT 30 Dec 93 </F>

<F P=103> EA3012203593 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Radio Mogadishu Voice of the 
Great Somali People </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Somali </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Thousands of Somalis today signed a petition for 
the withdrawal of foreign forces from Somalia so that the Somali 
people can achieve total peace and understanding. The petition 
is addressed to the UN Security Council and will go via the 
British Government. 
  The petition begins as follows: The NEW DAWN [WAAGA CUSUB] 
newspaper has been asked to campaign for this petition, which is 
the wish of Somali National Alliance [SNA] supporters in 
particular and the Somali people in general. It asks the UN 
Security Council for UN Forces to leave their country and 
release the officials and supporters who were illegally arrested 
and taken from their homes, and who are still in UN Operation in 
Somalia jails. The objective is to let the UN Security Council 
and the international community know the true feelings of the 
Somali people. [passage omitted] 
  [Paris AFP in English at 1146 GMT on 30 December in a 
Mogadishu-datelined item adds: "The petition signed by Aidid's 
supporters in Mogadishu accuses the United Nations of human 
rights abuses, including the detention of Osman Hassan Ali, 
known as `Ato', Aidid's chief financier who was arrested on 
September 21. Two other senior Aidid aides, Omar Salad Elmi and 
Mohamed Hassan Awale, have been held since October 3. The 
petition reiterates Aidid's assertion that the United Nations 
wants trying to colonize Somalia and accuses the world body of 
"creating a hostile atmosphere" by attacks against Aidid's 
faction, causing "the death and injury of an estimated 11,000 
Somali civilians." An Aidid supporter, Abdi Abshir Kahiye, said 
the SNA hoped to hand the petition to UN special envoy to 
Somalia, Jonathan Howe, with more than 50,000 signatures by the 
end of January."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

