<F P=100> REPUBLIC of SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urged To Uphold Law, Order </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB3112110793 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1028 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> MB3112110793 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pretoria Dec 31 SAPA -- The shooting of innocent 
people in Cape Town was part of the carnage taking place 
countrywide, which had increased since implementation of the 
Transitional Executive Council [TEC], AVF [Afrikaner National 
Front] spokesman Stephen Maninger said on Friday. 
  In its reaction to Thursday's night terror attack in Cape 
Town, the AVF called on the government and State President F W 
de Klerk to stop shadow-boxing with mere election statements, as 
though the country was in a peaceful election campaign. 
"Instead it should not evade its responsiblities to uphold law 
and order even if the TEC seems to have the de facto power," 
said Mr Maninger. 
  Government negotiator Roelf Meyer could use this opportunity 
to prove his past statements that implementation of the TEC did 
not rob the government of its power. "It is clear to us that 
since the TEC has come into effect there is a definite increase 
in violence. We believe that this is possibly the result of the 
fact that the same organisations actively conducting terror 
operations against political opponents are perhaps also playing 
a major role in the decision-making process within the TEC." 
  In view of the increasing violence, Mr de Klerk's recent 
electioneering attacks on his political opponents were not only 
pathetic and fake but reminded the AVF of Nero playing the 
fiddle while Rome was burning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

