<H3> <TI>   APLA Commander Threatens Natal, Tourists, ANC </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0201120594 Johannesburg SUNDAY STAR in English 02 Jan 94 p 
4 </F>

<F P=103> MB0201120594 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SUNDAY STAR </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mohseen Jeenah] </F>
  [Text] Natal is to be targeted by the Azanian People's 
Liberation Army [Apla] this year, an Apla unit commander 
threatened in an exclusive interview. The commander, who asked 
to be labelled by his combat name of "Sizwe", said small attacks 
had already been carried out in the province and that more would 
follow, urging people to leave "Occupied Azania." 
  "In line with Apla's declaration that 1993 was the year of 
the great storm, Apla units in Natal will pounce on the enemy. 
The year will end with a thunder in Natal. This holiday will 
be a bloody one. All the tourists in occupied Azania must leave 
if they want to live." 
  Sizwe also threatened that the ANC's [African National 
Congress] armed wing, Umkhonto we Sizwe [Spear of the Nation, 
MK], could soon become a target of Apla. "If MK joins the 
peacekeeping force, then they will become legitimate targets." 

