<F P=100> REPUBLIC of SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bophuthatswana Denies Military Defecting to MK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0201123894 Johannesburg SAPA in English 1205 GMT 02 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> MB0201123894 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg SAPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mmabatho Jan 2 SAPA -- Bophuthatswana denied on 
Sunday there had been defections in the homeland's Defence Force 
to the African National Congress' military wing, Umkhonto We 
Sizwe (MK). Homeland defence chief Maj-Gen H S Turner branded as 
"cheap propanga" a CITY PRESS newspaper report on Sunday saying 
a 22-man detachment of MK members had been formed in 
Bophuthatswana. 
  The members, some of whom were allegedly involved in the 
abortive 1988 military coup to topple President Lucas Mangope, 
had defected from the homeland's army. 
  The "Bop Platoon" was introduced during the ANC army's 32nd 
anniversary celebrations in Krugersdorp recently. MK's western 
Transvaal Chief of Staff Kagiso Ramatlhoko said the group had 
undergone military training under the auspices of MK. He told 
CITY PRESS the unit was based in the homeland, but he declined 
to disclose its location for security reasons. 
  Gen Turner dismissed the report as a "sham story". "The 
Bophuthatswana Defence Force [BDF] rejects allegations 
concerning the so-called defection of BDF members to the MK," he 
said. "The BDF considers the allegations cheap propaganda...It 
is again emphasised that MK activities in any form will not be 
tolerated in Bophuthatswana." 

</TEXT>

