<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Liberia </F>
<H3> <TI>   NPFL Not To Disarm Until Transition Bodies Set Up </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB3112175393 Paris AFP in English 1735 GMT 31 Dec 93 </F>
<F P=103> AB3112175393 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Monrovia, Dec 31 (AFP) -- The rebel National 
Patriotic Front of Liberia (NPFL), the country's main armed 
faction, said Friday [31 December] that [it] would only disarm 
its troops when transitional institutions were officially 
established. This position, announced by NPFL radio, is 
diametrically opposed to that of the Interim Government of 
National Unity (IGNU), which has said that such institutions can 
only become functional once disarmament begins. 
  According to the inter-factional peace accord signed by the 
IGNU, the NPFL and ULIMO (United Liberation Movement) on July 25 
in Cotonou, Benin, disarmament should be carried out 
simultaneously with the setting up of transitional institutions. 
  The NPFL also contested the presence in Liberia of the 
ECOMOG 
[Economic Community of West African States Cease-Fire Monitoring 
Group] peacekeeping force deployed by the Economic Community of 
West African States (ECOWAS), which -- assisted by the UN 
Observer Mission in Liberia (UNOMIL) -- is to supervise the 
disarmament process. 
  "Only the five-member State Council (the tripartite interim 
governing body) can provisionally authorize the deployment of 
foreign troops throughout the country," the NPFL said. 
  "For UNOMIL and ECOMOG to be deployed throughout the 
country, 
an agreement between the legitimate government of Liberia and 
the United Nations and another between the government and ECOWAS 
must be signed," it added. "Only the State Council has the 
authority to order the parties to remove checkpoints, gates, and 
the actual physical disarmament of all parties." 
  "Men, women, and ordinary citizens took up arms against the 
past government because it was not representative and did not 
address their concerns and grievances," said the NPFL, which was 
behind the rebellion that began on December 24, 1989, against 
the government of President Samuel Doe, who was assassinated in 
September 1990. 
  "Now that they have decided upon a legitimately accepted 
government in which they are represented, they are prepared to 
peacefully and voluntarily surrender their arms to that 
authority," it said. "Give them their government and they will 
give up their arms." 
  In the meantime, France on Friday condemned recent attacks 
against humanitarian organizations in northern Liberia, which 
forced them to withdraw from the area, calling on all factions 
to "show restraint." 
  Lucette Michauyx-Chevry, the French minister in charge of 
humanitarian aid and human rights, demanded "that confiscated 
materiel and equipment be returned to the organizations, that 
civilian populations be protected, and that the security of 
humanitarian organizations' personnel be guaranteed." 
  The UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Medecins sans 
Frontieres (MSF), and several other humanitarian organizations 
announced their withdrawal from northern Lofa County on December 
27, citing harassment from the armed ULIMO faction. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-43276 </DOCNO>
