<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Togo </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Threatens To Withdraw Electoral Help </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0101215594 Libreville Africa No. 1 in French 0730 GMT 1 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AB0101215594 </F>
<F P=104>  Libreville Africa No. 1 </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] France has threatened to withdraw its electoral 
assistance to Togo if conditions are not met for the holding of 
a fair legislative election on 23 January and 6 February. This 
was stated by Richard Duque, spokesman of the French Foreign 
Affairs Ministry. In a statement published yesterday, Richard 
Duque pointed out that right now, material conditions for a fair 
and democratic election have not been met, adding that the 
review of voters register and the distribution of the voting 
cards have encountered a preoccupying delay. 
  He added that France has decided, in conformity with the 11 
July Ouagadougou Accords, to send security and military 
observers to Togo in the coming days to join the Burkinabe 
military observers. French experts who are assisting in the 
electoral preparations have already started their work together 
with experts from other countries. However, Richard Duque said, 
France has stated that it will have to withdraw all of its 
observer team staff and its electoral assistance if conditions 
for a fair, democratic, and multiparty election are not met when 
the electoral campaign opens. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

