<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Cote d'Ivoire </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bedie Denounces `Neo-Colonialism' in Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0101104294 Paris AFP in English 0248 GMT 1 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0101104294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Abidjan, Jan 1 (AFP) -- Ivory Coast President Henri 
Konan Bedie, in his first speech Friday [31 December] since 
succeeding the late Felix Houphouet-Boigny, denounced the 
neo-colonialism gripping the West African nation's economy. 
  "It is not right that our industry should find itself back 
in 
the doldrums, that a large part of our wholesale and retail 
industry has fallen into the hands of foreigners and that our 
farm exports are still subject to a trading system that bears an 
irritating resemblance to the aberrations of the colonial era," 
he said in a year end address to the nation. 
  Konan Bedie, who succeeded to the presidency after 
Houphouet-Boigny's death on December 7, said the country needed 
quick solutions that could put the country back on the rails. 
  He added that the country was on the road to recovery when 
it 
came to balancing the budget and trade deficit. 

</TEXT>

