<F P=100> WEST AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Guinea-Bissau </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Comments on Trial for Alleged Coupists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB0501181394 Paris AFP in French 1826 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB0501181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lisbon, 4 Jan (AFP) -- President Joao Bernardo 
Vieira has assured that the trial of about 50 Guinea-Bissau 
opposition members accused of an attempted coup, including Joao 
da Costa the chairman of the Party for Renovation and 
Development, will be conducted fairly and legally. 
  "I guarantee that this trial will be conducted in the strict 
observance of the laws in force in the country and in line with 
international rules in the matter," the Guinea-Bissau head of 
state said in his answer to Portuguese head of state, Mario 
Soares, who wrote to him at the end of December to express the 
hope of seeing "caution" and "openness" guide this trial. 
  President Vieira, in his letter published by the LUSA AGENCY 
just before the opening of the trial on 4 January, denies the 
allegations that the date of da Costa's trial was set up 
hastily. "All the steps of the criminal procedure have been 
scrupulously observed," President Vieira assured in his letter 
to Mr. Soares. 

</TEXT>

