<F P=100> REPUBLIC OF SOUTH AFRICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Compares Attitudes About Future </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MB0601172394 Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network in 
English 1600 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> MB0601172394 </F>
<F P=104>  Johannesburg Radio South Africa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Blacks are twice as optimistic as whites about the 
year ahead. This has emerged from a Markinor Gallup poll which 
shows that 60 percent of blacks and only 31 percent of whites 
think conditions will improve in 1994. Optimism has improved 
markedly among blacks with 29 percent more than last year being 
positive about prospects. This is in sharp contrast to last 
year when blacks and whites were equally pessimistic about the 
future. Coloreds and Indians are only slightly less optimistic 
than blacks. Close on 60 percent of blacks and just over 40 
percent of coloreds feel that there will be fewer strikes this 
year. Forty percent of whites and 40 percent of Indians believe 
industrial strife will increase. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

